,Recommended,219780,25420,"Posted: 15 May, 2013",all,TheEvilBob,"I'm surprised I hadn't heard more about this game earlier; it was fun, funny, and featured a pretty compelling story.The graphics are a touch dated looking but nothing so antiquated that you can't look past, just something that would have been pretty cutting edge a few years ago. The art direction was a fairly typical high-fantasy look without going too wild. As 'real' a world as you're likely to see in this genre.The music was extremely well done. Not much more to say about that. It was very good.Gameplay was mostly smooth, there seemed to be some issues with jumping and it became advisable to always jump just a little ahead of what you thought you'd need. There were also some issues with clipping on objects but didn't occur often enough for me to get frustrated by it.Levelling was very smooth - each level actually made you feel more powerful but never took you to a point where there was no challenge at all. Different builds (Can't really call them classes, it's a classless system, you just choose the talents that you want and level them up as far as you want) may get different mileage but by the time I was near the end of the game the only thing I really had to watch out for were large groups of ranged or magic users since my health was tightly tied to hurting things.Overall it felt like a slightly more primitive version of Dragon Age in many ways. Certainly preferable to what they did to DA2! Also, no spoilers, but you WILL feel like you've been kicked in the neck at the end of the game, don't worry, the expansion makes up for it.Yeah... the expansion. I should mention that you don't import your character and you don't start with any of the gear you had, or indeed any at all, just enough gold to help buy things to get you back on your feet. Also, it takes away your shape-shifting ability until right at the end, that felt a bit dickish. So, while the 'world' was smaller and the play more limited, it 