,Recommended,219780,19835890,"Posted: 21 December, 2015",all,JuStX2,"Simply put this is a arche-typical Fantasy-setting RPG - Single Player only.Some things people may be wary of are:1. The Hint system (mind read) is used by expending Level up XP to use. While this is what the description says, it's not so much expending as extending, and what I mean by that is you never really *lose* the experience you already have, you just go into what's called ""Experience Debt"" which has to be repaid before you can continue to gain normal experience.2. The Tutorial Assumes you are already firmiliar with at a minimal RPGs, and probably assumes too much about your experience with action-games. What I mean by this is: The Tutorial doesn't go over more ""basic"" RPG Elements such as ""Equipment"" or ""Gear"" let alone ""leveling"" but it does give you basic controls. What I mean by it assumes too much about your experience with Action Games is...for the tutorial to cover controls is fine, but more of the advanced moves (ie rolling/jumping/dodging) are not well explained until AFTER you need them. Long Story short - the tutorials are very basic, and could use some polishing towards total newbies.3. Although the game is a bit dated (circa 2008 - 2009) the actual game-play/graphics details and other ""Preformance Effecting"" Details are quite up-to-par with modern standards. This game was obviously ahead of it's time even though it's time was a while back.***WARNING: The Next Few Sections MAY contain some spoilers. Reader Descretion is advised***4. I have -not- encountered any spiders - yet. I have to make mention of this because this is something I personally like, but realize not everyone wants. To Progress roughly 20~ Hours into the main-line quest stream and not see a single spider (albeit some webs) enemy is a good thing to me, because I am among those who are afraid of spiders (however - I am most certainly NOT afraid of Scorpions so I'm not ""Archnophobic"" by a typical detail). Mostly the Enemies I *have* encountered are undead/humanoid/demihuman types. Ie 2 Legs 2 Arms and Some Form of head and torso. The ghosts have no legs just two draping sheets tho.5. The Dragon Form - about the dragon form, although it cross-interfaces with the human form it feels more like the enemies are split into Dragon-Class (flying/structure mostly) and Human-class Enemies, and there is little combination of the two. Although you can fight some dragon-class enemies with a bow, the structures and such will not fire at a human. Moreover - the Ability/Skill system is only slightly different between human and dragon abilities, the major difference being you have (afaik) no ""Natural"" Skill Points in Dragon Abilities (you have to read some kinda book to get points etc). Also Although the Human form regenerates overtime at a variable rate - dragon form only heals when actively healed (ie with a spell/ability) which means you'll be using alot more of your dragon time using abilities rather than breathing fire.*** END -Possible- Spoilers ***Overall the game is good enough that I'd continue to play it for quite some time, however the aforementioned flaws are some of the things I wish had been explained to me before I found out on my own (which took some time)The Story in particular is excellently told, and personally I find myself continuing to play the game mostly because the story is so mysterious and intriguing. Good Example, One quest (which I have yet to complete) has you facing against a ""Veggie"" Witch, which to say nothing of the comedic standpoints is very unique among the thoughts of curses when someone evaluates a game such as this. Well-thought out the story is, but at times is just plain comedic to be sure. The Main Plot is no laughing matter though, but I'll leave that for you to discover. Advice: Get Used to Dying even on the easiest settings if you don't pay attention to what your doing. On the other hand, on the easiest settings there comes a point at which you become nigh invinicible late game."
