,Not Recommended,219780,26701336,"Posted: 19 November, 2016",all,ArYahn,"Let me get a couple things out of the way. First, I don't consider this to be a ""bad"" game in spite of the glaring red mark, but I can't really see myself recommending it to anyone either. Second there are some pretty terrible graphics issues right out of the gate, and if you do decide to pick it up I strongly encourage you to check out the pcgaming wiki page for it, as well as updating all relevant software. I admit that I haven't finished the game at this point, but I've also lost any interest in continuing.The combat in Divinity 2 is pretty comparable to something like World of Warcraft, you get a skillbar and a number of passive(dull minor % buffs) and active skills. The skills you can learn are limited by only your character level, which is pretty cool as it allows you to be open and creative with how you build your character, avoid the various crap skills, etc. When actually putting them into practice though, I found that it was the usual tedious rinse repeat of skill rotations, and for the most part enemies were easily avoided, especially early on. After a few hours in the game you'll run into quite a large number of enemies whose attacks cannot be avoided though: spell casters with instant hit point blasts, archers whose normal attacks can usually be avoided but whose special skills curve through the air magically tracking you. In fact a couple of the more annoying boss battles I experienced were against archers who had an undodgable stun (something like four seconds!), that they followed up with an explosive shot and various other attacks. The first of these encounters I had to cheese by exploiting line of sight, the second one I eventually realized could be blinded, and I wound up reloading until I got a successful blind before being stunned and gibbed. Ugh, and enemy healers, just annoying. Or maybe I'm just a bit jealous because when I got out of tougher fights in the earlier portions of the game I had to prance about looking for something else to do while waiting for my Hitpoints and Mana to ever so slowly crawl back up. Thankfully they seem to recover when you're in dialogs and inventory screens.The autosave function is a joke. In my playthrough I could count on it triggering maybe once every 3 hours. It's a bit painful to discover that after coming from more modern titles, but then the quicksave instinct quickly returns...and allows for any imaginable amount of save scumming you are comfortable with. Spend XP to mindread someone then reload? Sure, why not? I actually made an effort not to do this, but it still feels like a design oversight.Ah, but you do get to turn into a dragon...after several hours carving through the first few areas of the game. It is great at first...buuuut it got old pretty quick for me. Dragon gameplay is completely segregated from human gameplay, which admittedly is kinda necessary to keep the human side relevant without putting in something like a ""dragon gauge"" or whatever. Still, it's kinda silly to not even be able to see enemies on the ground while you're in dragon mode. In one instance I was flying around inside a giant cavern disabling barriers to get at a necromancer, when I dropped the last one I was expecting to be able deliver a big ol' dragon ♥♥♥♥♥smack, but no one was there. I transform to human and land and the necromancer is there ready to take me on. Great. Transform back into dragon, he runs off and disappears into the aether. Very disappointing. At first playing as the dragon felt empowering and kind of awesome, but then it quickly felt very easy and also inconsequential, because nothing I did as a dragon was going to make my human life much better.The writing kinda reminds me of various bioware games as far as the overall plot goes, but without much of the binary  meter driven morality. Most of the dialog options didn't seem to matter all that much though, and seemed to amount to a binary I am or am not being an ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ here. NPCs are eh, believable if not charming, fully voiced except for the main character which is impressive. Their animations seem pretty spastic at times for my taste, but it's pretty good still. No NPC party members outside of some short quest related instances, at least for the duration of my playthrough. I feel like that would've made a large difference in my impression of the game too, so more's the pity.The game holds up fairly well visually and has some amusing if simple puzzles, and clever tricks here and there. There is definitely some respectable take away if you can stand the lackluster combat and mechanics, being trapped in a room after quicksaving, etc."
