76561198038676788,Recommended,219780,8204053,"Posted: 22 December, 2013",all,Blademaster,"A very underrated game, Divinity II captured my attention a few years ago when Dragon Knight's saga had been released. The combat is relatively simple, yet it feels very sweet, especially near the endgame when you're taking on literal hordes of enemies, cutting them all down with superior damage.While I found the experience very fun, I can't help but mention glaring problems I had with the game, for one, the skill system was clearly geared for only damage dealers, there was nothing that I felt, would've fit a support/tank build, (which is understandable, since this is a SP game), but it got worse as I went forward, realizing how stupidly powerful I was with Dual wielding vs. any other set (especially against Bows, Bows really fell short in the end game). More specifically, the life drain skill was incredibly powerful at later levels, to the point where my high damage, low defense character was clearing rooms and never having to pop a potion or use a heal.Another issue I had was that the game felt clearly rushed, as the environment and characters all felt very shallow, with little of anything that you could actually do, outside of reading everyone's mind or doing missions. With very little characterization of non main plot characters, (with exception to a few), I felt that completing side missions was really just an excuse to get more XP, and since monsters don't respawn (until the endgame) its really the only choice. Though that in itself is a good thing, I just wish the side-missions felt a little more fun and engaging.Despite all this, I would reccommend D2 to a friend, because the main storyline itself, is very engaging and quite good. I hope Larian (the developers) will make a D3 and get the backing of a larger publishing company so they can use the additional resources and time that they deserve for their works."
