,Recommended,219780,32003121,Posted: 27 May,all,✚Cy4G✚ Jack-Senpai,"I got this game when it was on sale, and I fully expected it to be about average quality. After playing it, I can say that if I had know how great it was going to be, I would have definitely payed full price for it.StoryGood, but not amazing, at least not until the second-half of the game. It's easy enough to follow, and there's lore abound, if you're into that stuff like I am. The story might not be the selling point of the game, but the writing certainly is. Side Quests and hidden secrets are positively everywhere, and you'll run into many interesting characters during your adventure if you venture off the beaten path a bit. Combining the compelling story and rich lore with the wealth of captivating characters, both those involved in quests and regular old NPCs, you're left with an adventure through a land that feels truly alive.GameplayMoving on to the gameplay, which had to be my favorite part of the whole experience. The game handles well in and out of combat, with a cohesive UI and a neat, uncluttered inventory management system. Item stats are easy to understand, and there's a built-in comparison system to see how a new piece of gear stacks up against your currently equipped weapon or armor. Weapons and armor in themselves offer a whole wealth of choices in themselves, with several weapon types to choose from, each with their own unique skills that can be unlocked on theextensiveskill tree. There's swords, bows, greatswords, axes, hammers, magic, shields, and even bare fists, all of which are viable. Dual wielding is an option, as well. And did I mention that all weapons and armor can be enchanted, granting additional stat boosts? If it sounds badass, that’s because it is. Combat is slick and fast-paced, and rarely feels sloppy. Skills unlocked from the aforementioned skill tree can be mapped to hotkeys, as can items, allowing for easy access during frantic battles, which often have you facing more than one enemy at once. By the end of the game, you’re facing small battalions of enemies, living out a classic power fantasy as you one-man-army them into oblivion.Not really a spoiler, but you also gain the power to transform into a dragon later on in the game, and itplays like a dream.Aerial combat is fast and exciting, and like ground combat, you have a large skill tree to invest points in, making your dragon form even more formidable. The sense of power felt in your dragon form is amazing, but I still feel that the dragon form is weaker than it should be. If you aren’t careful, you can get swarmed and taken down by a few airborne pests. Your dragon form is like a glass cannon, in a way, where as I feel that it should have been more like a flying tank. You’re a dragon, for crying out loud. Still, playing as the winged behemoth that you’re so often forced to fight in other games is euphoric in a way that I can’t really describe, and it’s definitely one of the things that sets this game apart. My only complaint is that when you enter dragon form, regular enemies on the ground disappear. Easily crushing large groups of enemies with the monstrous power of your dragon form would have been a dream come true for me, but it would have made playing in human form nearly obsolete, so I understand why they left that feature out.SoundThe overall sound quality of Divinity II is very high. The voice acting is amazing, enhancing the aforementioned outstanding writing. Unlike in Skyrim, you don’t run into the problem of every other character being voiced by the same actor, which would easily break immersion. Instead, many characters have unique voices you only hear from them. The SFX are also well done, with the clang of your weapons against enemy armor providing a sense of weight and impact. The music, however, is probably the weakest part of the sound package. While fitting, it certainly isn’t the most memorable soundtrack out there. It’s not bad by any stretch of the word, but just isn’t something that will stick in your head for weeks after playing it.GraphicsThe graphics are, well, kind of dated. It’s certainly not at the level of GTA 5 or NieR, but the game came out in 2009, so I would argue that it deserves a little slack. That being said, the lands you adventure through are bright and colorful, and the various dungeons and locales you find yourself exploring aren’t nearly as generic as some other games. The character models are fairly detailed, and the lip-syncing is well done. Having somewhat dated graphics also means that it doesn’t take a top of the line pc to play it in it’s finest form, which is a welcome change in a market full of games designed with only the highest specs in mind. While the graphics might not be the strongest point of the game, not once did I feel that it detracted from my experience.ConclusionDivinity II is a wonderful action-RPG, positively brimming with content and charm, offering a lively world full of quests to complete, secrets to find, and foes to slay. If you can find it on sale, I would wholeheartedly recommend grabbing it."
