76561198007348269,Recommended,219780,31519036,Posted: 2 May,all,TheSilentType,"Question.Do you like Dragons?I ask this because your answer will also probably answer how much you'll like this game.That is because the key selling point of this game is that your human character can transform into a DRAGON. Not for all of it (boo) and not everywhere in the game (BOO) but for a good chunk of it you can simply press a button and rain fiery, winged death down on anyone stupid enough to remain in the immediate vicinity. In this game you can assault vast flying fortresses as a dragon, tear their defences down, have aerial dogfights with flying demons, then morph back into a human and cut your way through courtyards until you kill the enemy general - all without a single cutscene. This can be a really fun game.The writing is also stellar, striking a fun balance between humor and seriousness; this only gets better in the sequel campaign where your character almost seems to start channeling Deadpool. This is my first Divinity title, so I can't say much about how it compares to others in the series but I thought the world was quite well handled, sticking to a lot of fantasy tropes while still putting them together in a unique enough way, my only real regret is that I didn't get to see more of it. The music is really good too.Sadly it is not without flaws. The combat, while fun and frantic in the later game can be frustrating early on (I highly recommend low level characters to always carry a bow). Your only method of avoiding attacks is to jump or dodge-roll, leading to you spending most fights rolling around enemies like a spiky, sword wielding barrel. Flying round areas in the late game is fun, but during the early game and the second campaign the amount of backtracking some quests require becomes annoying. I also encountered a few crashes during loading screens; nothing that couldn't be worked around but still annoying.Divinity 2 is not as polished as the likes of Dragon Age, but play it for any length of time and you'll see the potential beneath the surface. It can be annoying, even frustrating at times, but those moments are brief. For the most part Divinity 2 is thoroughly enjoyable, and when it embraces the things that make it unique it becomes downright spectacular."
,Recommended,219780,31562597,Posted: 5 May,all,Suigeneris_,"Good game, it's really got an old school RPG charm to it that I enjoy. Mechanics are simple to grasp and the world is interesting and fun to explore. One you hit a certain point though, the difficulty ratchets way up (you'll know what I mean when you get there). The combat seems to be geared towards ranged attackers, especially later on, so I would not recommend starting as a melee class. Worth picking up on sale if you're a fan of old school PC RPG's. No controller support by the way"
